| 1905 || {{dts|August 11}} || Legislation || Executive branch, specifically home ministry || The {{w|Aliens Act 1905}} is the first Act to introduce immigration controls and registration. The {{w|Home Secretary}} is given overall responsibility for immigration and nationality matters. While the Act is ostensibly designed to prevent paupers and criminals from migrating and to deport those who migrated, its unstated motivation seems to be to control Jewish immigration from Eastern Europe.
|-
| 1914 || {{dts|August 5}} || Legislation || Executive branch, specifically home ministry || The {{w|Aliens Restriction Act 1914}} is passed in a single day on the eve of {{w|World War I}}. The Act requires every person entering the country to produce evidence of identity at the time of entry. The Act effectively supersedes the Aliens Act 1905 due to much more stringent provisions.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documentsonline/aliens.asp |title= Aliens Registration Cards |publisher=[[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives]] |accessdate=25 August 2011}}</ref> The power still remains in use.<ref>https://www.gov.uk/register-with-the-police</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1914/12/pdfs/ukpga_19140012_en.pdf|title = Aliens Restriction Act, 1914|accessdate = November 19, 2017}}</ref>
|-
| 1920 || || || || The {{w|UK Immigration Service}} begins operation under the {{w|Home Office}}, under the name of '''Aliens Branch'''.
|-
| 1925 || || || || By this time, an immigration officer is present at {{w|Croydon Airport}}, the UK's main airport (taken from Wikipedia page, no citation present).
|-
| 1933 || || || || The Aliens Branch changes its name to the '''Immigration Branch'''. The most recent name prior to being disbanded is {{w|UK Immigration Service}}.
|-
| 1973 || || || || The Immigration Branch changes its name to the {{w|UK Immigration Service}}.
|-
| 1987 || || || || The Carriers' Liability Act is passed. The Act places liability on carriers for passengers they bring without proper documents.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1987/24/enacted|title = Immigration (Carriers' Liability) Act 1987|accessdate = November 19, 2017}}</ref>
|-
| 1993 || || || || The {{w|Campsfield House}} deention centre is opened. This is to provide the Immigration Service with additional capacity of 200 to detail people, beyond the 180 or so places available at airports.
|-
| 1993 || || || || The first Airline Liaison Officer (ALO) is posted in the Delhi airport, to prevent people from boarding if they have suspect documentation. ALO deployments would increase over the year, reaching 57 by 2001. The number of passengers prevented from boarding would reach 2095 in 1998 and 4999 in 1999.
|-
| 1998 || {{dts|July 27}} || || || Under the Labour government of 1997 to 2001, the document '''Fairer, Faster And Firmer - a modern approach to immigration and asylum''' is published by the Home Office.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/fairer-faster-and-firmer-a-modern-approach-to-immigration-and-asylum|title = Fairer, Faster And Firmer - a modern approach to immigration and asylum|publisher = United Kingdom Home Office|date = July 27, 1998|accessdate = November 21, 2017}}</ref> The paper promises an expansion of detention centres, and leads to a lot of detention centre construction.
|-
| 2000 || {{dts|February 6}} || || || A group of hijackers led by brothers Ali Safi and Mohammed Safi hijack a local flight in Afghanistan to fly to and land at {{w|Stansted Airport}} in Essex. 79 of the passengers claim asylum in the United Kingdom. This would lead to a court case that would lead to judicial rulings in 2006 stating that the hijackers' actions do not make them ineligible for asylum. Both parties condemn the rulings, and opposition blames them on the Labour Party's {{w|Human Rights Act 1998}}. See {{W|2006 Afghan hijackers case}} for more.
|-
| 2001 || {{dts|February}} || || || The Immigration and Nationality Directorate's (IND) Casework Application Programme contract with Siemens Business Services is cancelled, after it is determined that Siemens would be unable to deliver what IND wants. The goal was to provide a strong information technology backbone for IND operations. The contract was signed in April 1996 for delivery in October 1998, but delivery had been repeatedly delayed prior to the cancellation of the contract.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.computerweekly.com/feature/Home-Office-cancels-key-immigration-IT-system|title = Home Office cancels key immigration IT system|last = Simons|first = Mike|date = February 1, 2001|accessdate = November 21, 2017}}</ref>
|-
| 2007 || {{dts|April 1}} || Organizational restructuring || Border and Immigration Agency; current equivalents: Immigration Enforcement, Border Force, UK Visas and Immigration || The {{w|Border and Immigration Agency}} (BIA) is created through as an executive agency of the British {{w|Home Office}}. It replaces the {{w|Immigration and Nationality Directorate}} (IND), and its operational arm, the {{w|UK Immigration Service}}.
|-
| 2008 || {{dts|April 1}} || Organizational restructuring || UK Border Agency; current equivalents: Immigration Enforcement, Border Force, UK Visas and Immigration || The {{w|UK Border Agency}} is created as part of the {{w|Home Office}}, through a merger of the {{w|Border and Immigration Agency}}, {{w|UKvisas}}, and the detection function of {{w|Her Majesty's Revenue and Customs}}. The agency would suffer a similar fate as the similar {{w|Immigration and Naturalization Service}} in the United States: it would be shut down and its functions handed over to more specific agencies.
|-
| 2012 || {{dts|March 1}} || Organizational restructuring || Border Force || The {{w|Border Force}} is spun off from the UK Border Agency. It controls air and sea ports of entry and also monitors the rest of the border. It is similar to {{w|U.S. Customs and Border Protection}}.
|-
| 2012 || {{dts|April 1}} || Organizational restructuring || Immigration Enforcement || {{w|Immigration Enforcement}} is spun off from the UK Border Agency. It carries out ''visits'' in residential and business premises to identify people present without an authorised status, and initiate removal proceedings. It is similar to {{w|U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement}}.
|-
| 2013 || {{dts|April 1}} || Organizational restructuring || UK Border Agency; current equivalents: Immigration Enforcement, Border Force, UK Visas and Immigration || The UK Border Agency is dissolved. Border Force and Immigration Enforcement already report directly to the Home Office; the visas function is spun off as {{w|UK Visas and Immigration}} (the UK equivalent of {{w|United States Citizenship and Immigration Services}}).
